        <h2>ETF Meaning</h2>
        <p>ETFs are a sort of investment fund that combines the best features of two popular assets: They combine the diversification benefits of mutual funds with the simplicity with which equities may be exchanged.</p>
        
        <h2>What is an ETF?</h2>
        <p>An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a collection of investments such as equities or bonds. ETFs will let you invest in a large number of securities at once, and they often have cheaper fees than other types of funds. ETFs are also more easily traded.</p>
        <p>However, ETFs, like any other financial product, is not a one-size-fits-all solution. Examine them on their own merits, including management charges and commission fees, ease of purchase and sale, fit into your existing portfolio, and investment quality.</p>
        
        <h2>How Do ETFs Work?</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>An ETF provider forms a fund to track performance and offers shares to investors.</li>
            <li>Shareholders own part of the ETF but not its underlying assets.</li>
            <li>Like stocks, ETFs are traded on an exchange throughout the day.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>Types of ETFs</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Index ETFs:</strong> Track a specific index.</li>
            <li><strong>Fixed Income ETFs:</strong> Provide exposure to bonds.</li>
            <li><strong>Commodity ETFs:</strong> Track prices of commodities like gold or oil.</li>
            <li><strong>Sector ETFs:</strong> Target specific industries like technology or pharmaceuticals.</li>
            <li><strong>International ETFs:</strong> Monitor non-Indian markets such as Japan's Nikkei Index.</li>
            <li><strong>Leveraged ETFs:</strong> Use leverage to boost returns.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>Benefits of Investing in ETFs</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Trade ETFs anytime during market hours.</li>
            <li>Daily reporting of holdings ensures transparency.</li>
            <li>Tax efficiency with fewer capital gain distributions.</li>
            <li>Flexibility to place advanced order types like limit or stop-loss orders.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>Risks of ETFs</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Transaction fees may add up for frequent small investments.</li>
            <li>Lightly traded ETFs may have large bid-ask spreads.</li>
            <li>Technical glitches can cause tracking errors.</li>
            <li>Settlement delays may restrict immediate reinvestment after selling ETFs.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>How to Invest in ETFs?</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Step 1: Open a brokerage account.</li>
            <li>Step 2: Choose the ETF that aligns with your goals.</li>
            <li>Step 3: Transfer the money and start investing.</li>
        </ol>
